article.description:
Adrienne Goodson scored 20 points, including
the go-ahead basket in overtime, as the Utah Starzz beat the
Minnesota Lynx 79-75 in the opener for both teams Saturday night.

related.description:
Minnesota's Katie Smith, the WNBA's leading
scorer last season, sat out the Lynx's season opener against the
Utah Starzz on Saturday night because of an injured right index
finger.

article.headline: Goodson leads Starzz to opening win
article.linkText: Starzz need overtime to get past Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Utah Starzz showed Minnesota that they can win without high-scoring Natalie Williams at her best. Adrienne Goodson scored 20 points, including the go-ahead basket in overtime, as Utah overcame Williams' problems to beat the Lynx 79-75 Saturday night in the opener for both teams. Jennifer Azzi and Margo Dydek each had 14 and Marie Ferdinand added 12 for Utah. Williams finished with nine points, going 4-for-8 from the field and 1-for-5 from the line. "Every position can score, we're fortunate to have a talented team. It's hard for a team to double anybody. It's like picking their poison,'' Ferdinand said. Fresh off their first playoff appearance, the Starzz cooled off Minnesota's shooting in the second half with strong perimeter defense, forcing the Lynx to drive inside against a bigger Utah front anchored by the 7-foot-2 Dydek. "We had some good stops at the end,'' Starzz coach Candi Harvey said. "I'm pleased we were able to get a road win.'' Svetlana Abrosimova had 26 points for the Lynx, who were without WNBA All-Star Katie Smith. Abrosimova was 7-of-17 from the field, including a pair of 3-pointers. But was 10-for-18 from the free thrown line. The Lynx had chances to tie or take the lead after Goodson's layup with 44.3 seconds left. But Abrosimova and Betty Lennox missed 3-pointers, and Michele Van Gorp -- whose two free throws with 14.5 seconds left in regulation forced overtime -- was called for an over-the-back foul. Azzi hit the second of two free throws to make it 78-75 with 14.3 seconds left. Lennox missed a 3-pointer, and Ferdinand hit a free throw to seal the victory. Abrosimova picked up the slack for Smith, who has an injured right index finger, but the Lynx couldn't match Utah's weapons. Lennox, who missed 21 games last season with a strained left hip capsule, scored 13 points in her first regular-season game since undergoing surgery in November. "We played too hard for this outcome,'' Lennox said. "We need to learn to capitalize on our opponents' mistakes. As a team, we can't give in at the end of games, because we don't want to start off this season like we did last year (when Minnesota started 1-4).'' Utah won despite giving up 30 points off 28 turnovers. Game notes
The Lynx, 3-1 in season openers, were 19-for-32 from the free-throw line. ... Rookies Tamika Williams and Shaunzinski Gortman are the only new faces on this year's Lynx roster. ... The Lynx honored Minnesota's 2002 high school girls state basketball champions and the Minnesota Golden Gophers women's basketball team at halftime. Pam Borton, hired as the Gophers' head coach Friday, received a standing ovation as she was introduced.
